05173nam a22007215i 9780691185712DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911857127 a10.1515/97806911857122doi  a(DE-B1597)528065  a(OCoLC)1083465232  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBH301.C4 7aPHI0010002bisacsh04a155.2/52231 aMay, Simon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Power of Cute /cSimon May. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- t1. Cute as a Weapon of Mass Seduction -- t2. Spooked in the Garden of Eden -- t3. Cute as an Uncertainty Principle -- t4. Mickey Mouse and the Cuteness Continuum -- t5. Kawaii: The New Japanese Imperium -- t6. The Cuteness of Kim Jong- il -- t7. Cute and the Uncanny -- t8. What's Wrong with Cute Anthropomorphism? -- t9. Cute and the Monstrous: The Case of Donald Trump -- t10. Cute and the New Cult of the Child -- t11. Survival of the Cutest -- t12. Cute and Kitsch: Identical Twins? -- t13. Exiting the Cult of Sincerity -- t14. "Lifetime Is a Child at Play" -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn exploration of cuteness and its immense hold on us, from emojis and fluffy puppies to its more uncanny, subversive expressionsCuteness has taken the planet by storm. Global sensations Hello Kitty and Pokémon, the works of artists Takashi Murakami and Jeff Koons, Heidi the cross-eyed opossum and E.T.-all reflect its gathering power. But what does "cute" mean, as a sensibility and style? Why is it so pervasive? Is it all infantile fluff, or is there something more uncanny and even menacing going on-in a lighthearted way? In The Power of Cute, Simon May provides nuanced and surprising answers.We usually see the cute as merely diminutive, harmless, and helpless. May challenges this prevailing perspective, investigating everything from Mickey Mouse to Kim Jong-il to argue that cuteness is not restricted to such sweet qualities but also beguiles us by transforming or distorting them into something of playfully indeterminate power, gender, age, morality, and even species. May grapples with cuteness's dark and unpindownable side-unnerving, artful, knowing, apprehensive-elements that have fascinated since ancient times through mythical figures, especially hybrids like the hermaphrodite and the sphinx. He argues that cuteness is an addictive antidote to today's pressured expectations of knowing our purpose, being in charge, and appearing predictable, transparent, and sincere. Instead, it frivolously expresses the uncertainty that these norms deny: the ineliminable uncertainty of who we are; of how much we can control and know; of who, in our relations with others, really has power; indeed, of the very value and purpose of power.The Power of Cute delves into a phenomenon that speaks with strange force to our age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAesthetics, Moderny21st century. 0aCharm. 0aChildishness. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2019 Englishz978311061055008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2019z9783110606423oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691185712zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.d